2.3 Bomb Calorimetry
Bomb Calorimeter – Measuring Energy Content
Principle: A known mass of sample is combusted in a sealed steel "bomb" under high-pressure On (30
atm). Heat released raises temperature of surrounding water bath. Temperature rise measured ® energy
content calculated.
Formula: Q = mcDT / m_sample
Where: Q = calorific value (kJ/g or MJ/kg); m = mass of water in calorimeter; c = specific heat of water (4.186
J/g·°C); DT = temperature rise; m_sample = mass of sample (g)
Gross Calorific Value (GCV) / Higher Heating Value (HHV): Total heat released including condensation
of water vapour
Net Calorific Value (NCV) / Lower Heating Value (LHV): GCV - latent heat of water vapour (2.442
MJ/kg per % H content)
Environmental applications:
• Calorific value of fuels (coal, biomass, RDF, waste)
• Energy content of solid waste for incineration feasibility
• BOD calculation check (ThOD via combustion stoichiometry)
• Proximate analysis of coal (moisture, ash, volatile matter, fixed carbon)
Typical calorific values: Coal 20–35 MJ/kg; Wood biomass 15–20 MJ/kg; MSW 8–12 MJ/kg; Petrol 44 MJ/kg
