3. Chromatography
Chromatography is a separation technique in which components of a mixture are distributed between a
stationary phase and a mobile phase. Components travel at different speeds depending on their affinity for each
phase, resulting in separation. Key parameter: Rf value (planar) or retention time (column).
3.1 Fundamental Principles
Core Chromatographic Concepts
Stationary phase: Solid or liquid fixed in place (silica gel, alumina, polymer beads, capillary coating)
Mobile phase: Liquid or gas that moves through/over the stationary phase (eluent/carrier gas)
Separation basis: Differential partitioning (distribution) of analytes between phases based on polarity,
size, charge, or specific interactions
Rf value (Retention factor): Rf = distance travelled by spot / distance travelled by solvent front (0–1;
used in TLC and PC)
Retention time (tR): Time for analyte to travel from injection to detector in column chromatography (GC,
HPLC)
Resolution (Rs): Rs = 2(tR2-tR1)/(w1+w2); Rs > 1.5 = baseline separation
Van Deemter equation: H = A + B/u + Cu (plate height vs flow rate; optimum flow for minimum H)
3.2 Paper Chromatography (PC)
Paper chromatography uses cellulose filter paper as the stationary phase (water held in cellulose fibres). The
mobile phase is an organic solvent or solvent mixture that moves up/across the paper by capillary action.
Feature Details
Stationary phase Cellulose paper (Whatman No. 1 most common); water held in fibres = true stationary phase
Mobile phase Organic solvent/mixtures: n-butanol:acetic acid:water; acetone; ethanol mixtures
Mode Ascending (most common), descending, radial/circular, 2D (two solvents at 90°)
Detection UV lamp (fluorescence); ninhydrin spray (amino acids ® purple); iodine vapour; chemical sprays
Rf value Rf = distance of spot / distance of solvent front; characteristic for each compound under defined
conditions
Applications Amino acid identification; plant pigment separation (chlorophylls, carotenoids); sugar analysis;
food dye testing; qualitative pesticide screening
Limitations Poor resolution; quantitative only with densitometry; not suitable for complex mixtures
