4. Flame Photometry
Flame photometry (flame emission spectroscopy) measures the intensity of light emitted by atoms when they
are excited in a flame and then return to ground state. It is used for alkali and alkaline earth metals at low cost
and high speed, making it ideal for soil and water analysis of Na, K, Li, Ca, Ba.
Flame Photometry – Principle and Setup
Atomisation: Sample aspirated into flame (propane-air or natural gas-air)
Excitation: Flame energy excites valence electrons to higher energy levels
Emission: Electrons fall back ® emit light at characteristic wavelengths
Detection: Photomultiplier tube behind interference filter selects specific wavelength
Quantitation: Intensity µ concentration (Beer-Lambert-like calibration curve)
Characteristic emission wavelengths:
Na = 589 nm (yellow); K = 766 nm (red-violet); Li = 671 nm (red; used as internal standard); Ca = 622 nm
(orange); Ba = 554 nm (green)
Internal standard method: Li added at constant concentration to all samples and standards ® corrects for flame
instability and matrix effects ® most accurate flame photometry
Environmental applications: Nan, Kn in drinking water/soil extracts; Ca²n hardness; Li as groundwater tracer
