6.2 X-Ray Fluorescence (XRF)
XRF – Non-Destructive Elemental Analysis
Principle: Primary X-rays bombard sample ® inner shell electrons ejected ® outer shell electrons fall in ®
emit characteristic fluorescent X-rays (secondary) at energies specific to each element
Energy Dispersive XRF (ED-XRF): All energies detected simultaneously; fast; portable; semi-quantitative
Wavelength Dispersive XRF (WD-XRF): Diffracts X-rays by crystal; scans wavelengths sequentially;
better resolution and sensitivity
Detection range: Na to U; detection limits ~mg/kg (ppm) in solid matrices
Advantages: Non-destructive; no sample dissolution; rapid; can analyse solids/liquids/filters directly
Environmental applications: Heavy metals in soil/sediment/dust; elemental composition of PMn.n filters; geological
mapping; Pb in paint (portable XRF); industrial waste characterisation
