XRD – Crystal Structure and Mineral Identification
Principle: X-rays diffracted by crystal lattice planes (Bragg's Law: nl = 2d sinq). Each crystalline mineral has
a unique d-spacing pattern (fingerprint).
Bragg's Law: nl = 2d sinq (n = integer; l = X-ray wavelength; d = interplanar
spacing; q = diffraction angle)
Output: Diffractogram (2q vs intensity); compared to JCPDS/ICDD database for mineral identification
Powder XRD (PXRD): Most common; polycrystalline material; identifies mineral phases in mixtures
Environmental applications:
• Clay mineral identification in soil (kaolinite, smectite, illite, chlorite)
• Iron oxide mineralogy in contaminated sediments (goethite, ferrihydrite, magnetite)
• Asbestos identification (chrysotile vs amphibole varieties)
• Scale/corrosion product identification in water pipes
• Nanoparticle characterisation (crystallite size via Scherrer equation)
