7. UGC NET Pattern MCQs with Explanations
Q1. In the determination of total hardness by EDTA titration, the indicator used at pH 10 is:
(a) Murexide
(b) Phenolphthalein
(c) Eriochrome Black T (EBT)
(d) Ferroin
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: EBT (Eriochrome Black T) is used for total hardness (Ca²n + Mg²n) titration. At pH 10 (ammonia
buffer), EBT forms a wine-red complex with metal ions. As EDTA is added, it preferentially complexes metals ® EBT
released ® turns blue = endpoint. Murexide is used for Ca-only titration at pH 12 (where Mg²n precipitates).
Q2. The Beer-Lambert Law states that absorbance (A) is:
(a) Inversely proportional to concentration
(b) Directly proportional to concentration and path length (A = ebc)
(c) Proportional to the square of concentration
(d) Independent of path length
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: Beer-Lambert Law: A = e × b × c, where e = molar absorptivity, b = path length (cm), c = concentration
(mol/L). Absorbance is directly and linearly proportional to both path length and concentration. Linear range: A =
0.1–1.0; above 1.0, the law fails (stray light, solution chemistry changes).
Q3. In Gas Chromatography, the ECD (Electron Capture Detector) is most suitable for:
(a) All organic compounds
(b) Sulphur-containing compounds
(c) Halogenated compounds such as OC pesticides and PCBs
(d) Nitrogen-containing compounds
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: ECD responds to compounds with electronegative atoms (halogens F, Cl, Br, I; nitro groups). It is the
most sensitive detector for organochlorine (OC) pesticides (DDT, Aldrin, Dieldrin) and PCBs, with detection limits of
10n¹n–10n¹³ g/s. FID is universal; FPD is for S and P; NPD/TID is for N and P compounds.
Q4. Which technique uses Bragg's Law (nl = 2d sinq) for analysis?
(a) X-Ray Fluorescence (XRF)
(b) X-Ray Diffraction (XRD)
(c) Fourier Transform Infrared (FTIR)
(d) Atomic Absorption Spectroscopy (AAS)
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: Bragg's Law describes the conditions for constructive interference of X-rays diffracted by crystal lattice
planes. XRD uses this to identify crystalline minerals and compounds by their unique d-spacing patterns. XRF uses
fluorescent X-ray emission (different principle). FTIR uses IR absorption. AAS uses light absorption by atoms.
Q5. ICP-MS has a significantly lower detection limit than ICP-AES because:
(a) It uses a hotter plasma temperature
(b) It detects ions by mass-to-charge ratio with high sensitivity, reaching ng/L–pg/L
(c) It can analyse more elements simultaneously
(d) It requires less sample preparation
UGC NET / JRF · Environmental Sciences (Code 89)
Unit II · Topic 2.7 – Analytical Methods: Titrimetry, Gravimetry, Chromatography & Spectroscopy
© UGC NET Env. Sci. Study Notes | Topic 2.7 Page 22
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: ICP-MS separates ions by m/z ratio using a mass analyser (quadrupole or sector field). The mass
spectrometer detects individual ions with very high efficiency ® detection limits of ng/L (ppt) to pg/L (ppq). ICP-AES
detects emitted photons (less sensitive). Both use the same Ar plasma. ICP-MS also allows isotope ratio
measurement.
Q6. In atomic absorption spectroscopy (AAS), the hollow cathode lamp is used because:
(a) It provides a broad spectrum for background correction
(b) It emits narrow spectral lines exactly matching the absorption wavelength of the analyte element
(c) It heats the sample to produce atomic vapour
(d) It ionises the sample in the plasma
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: The hollow cathode lamp (HCL) contains the same element being analysed. When current passes
through, atoms of that element are sputtered and emit narrow, element-specific spectral lines. These match exactly
the absorption wavelengths of the same element in the sample ® highly selective measurement. A separate lamp is
needed for each element.
Q7. FTIR spectroscopy identifies an unknown compound. A strong absorption band at 1715 cmn¹ is
observed. This band is most likely due to:
(a) O-H stretch (alcohol or water)
(b) N-H bend (amine)
(c) C=O stretch (carbonyl group)
(d) C-H stretch (alkane)
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: The C=O (carbonyl) stretching vibration is one of the strongest and most characteristic IR absorptions. It
occurs at 1700–1750 cmn¹: aldehydes ~1725; ketones ~1715; carboxylic acids ~1710; esters ~1735. O-H stretch =
3200–3600; C-H stretch = 2850–3000; N-H = 1550–1650. The fingerprint region is 500–1500 cmn¹.
Q8. The Rf value in Thin Layer Chromatography (TLC) is defined as:
(a) The ratio of solvent front distance to compound spot distance
(b) The ratio of distance travelled by compound to distance travelled by solvent front
(c) The retention time of the compound on the TLC plate
(d) The resolution factor between two adjacent spots
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: Rf = distance travelled by compound spot / distance travelled by solvent front. Rf values range from 0
(did not move from origin) to 1 (moved with solvent front). Each compound has a characteristic Rf under specific
conditions (solvent system, stationary phase, temperature). Used to identify compounds by comparison with
reference standards run on the same plate.
