n Final Exam Strategy for Topic 2.7
1. Titration indicators: EBT=total hardness; Murexide=Ca hardness; Phenolphthalein=P-alkalinity;
Methyl orange=T-alkalinity; Starch=iodometric DO; Ferroin=COD. Must memorise all.
2. Beer-Lambert: A=ebc; A=-log(T); linear range 0.1–1.0. Key wavelengths: POn³n=880nm;
NOnn=543nm; Fe=510nm; NHnn=630nm.
3. GC detectors: FID=universal organics; ECD=halogenated (OC pesticides, PCBs); FPD=S and P (OP
pesticides); NPD=N and P; MS=definitive ID.
4. HPLC: RP-HPLC with C18 column = most common; polar mobile phase; Ion Chromatography = anions
(Fn, Cln, NOnn, SOn²n) with conductivity detector.
5. AAS hierarchy: GFAAS (ng/L) > FAAS (μg/L); CV-AAS = only Hg; HG-AAS = As, Se, Sb.
6. ICP: ICP-AES = multi-element at μg/L; ICP-MS = ultra-trace at ng/L–pg/L + isotope ratios + speciation
(LC-ICP-MS).
7. XRD: Bragg's Law nl=2d sinq; identifies MINERALS; JCPDS database. XRF: identifies ELEMENTS
non-destructively; cannot speciate oxidation states.
8. FTIR: C=O at 1700–1750 cmn¹; O-H at 3200–3600; C-H at 2850–3000. ATR-FTIR = no sample prep.
Used for microplastic and SOM analysis.
